kb:graph-as-navigation
    rdfs:label "Graph-as-Site-Navigation" ;
    pred:feature-id "F49" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:relates-to kb:knowledge-graph ;
    pred:description "Make published pages first-class citizens of the graph so the graph itself is the site map. PARTS: (1) WebPage nodes (ktype:WebPage, F27) RENDER as graph nodes — visible alongside concepts, distinguishable (icon/type), selectable. (2) In-graph site structure: define a LANDING/home page and navigation to SUBPAGES as graph edges (reuse skos:broader for parent/child + nav:next/prev for sequence, the same hierarchy vocabulary the hnav trees use), created and rearranged in the graph. (3) LIGHT-FORCE nav edges — CRITICAL: page/nav edges must carry a much lower force-directed spring weight than concept edges, because a nav hub connected to many published pages (or pages linked across every concept) would otherwise collapse/warp the main graph shape. Introduce per-edge-kind force weights (concept edges normal; page/nav edges very light, or excluded from the main force pass and laid out in a secondary/orbit pass) so adding the whole published site never distorts the knowledge layout. (4) In-graph PAGE METADATA editing: edit slug, section, template, status, title from the node panel (writes the urn:kbase:page/* triples; round-trips via F27 site-export + md-align). (5) Publishing map: from any concept, see which pages reference/derive from it and jump to them; from a page node, open the published /docs URL. Builds on F27 graph publishing and relates to F46 (question-context pages, another in-graph page attach), the 2D/3D graph (per-edge force weights), and the /docs route." ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:relates-to kb:question-context-pages ;
    pred:principle "The graph is the PRIMARY navigation of what pages are published and where they're accessed — not a separate site-map UI. Publishing structure lives in, and is edited from, the graph." ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:has-status "planned" .

kb:local-model-bench
    pred:depends-on kb:mcp-server ;
    pred:has-status "functional" ;
    pred:feature-id "F31" ;
    pred:in-dev "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:tested-by "tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts" ;
    rdfs:label "Local Model Benchmarking & Orchestration" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:ci-cd-kb-watch ;
    pred:tested-by "tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts" ;
    pred:tested-by "tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts" ;
    pred:tested-by "tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts" ;
    pred:description "Evidence-driven selection of LOCAL models for agent grunt work: keep the strong cloud model (Opus) on the main/orchestration thread and delegate bulk work to local Ollama models via `ollama launch` integrations (claude/opencode/etc.) on a local multi-GPU Ollama host — zero API cost, private. Two reproducible benchmarks pick the right local model per role. (1) VLM visual-gate bench — tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts + vlm-golden.ts — scores local vision models as 'does this appear' gates against human-verified screenshot labels (10 images, 48 checks across 7 capability types: toast/mobile/graph/blank/settings/kb/align-tab); the gate score weights recall highest (a miss waves a real regression through — the one intolerable error) plus precision, accuracy, and latency. A cheap local VLM screens every screenshot; only its flags escalate to the expensive reviewer (Opus/Claude Vision). Result: qwen2.5vl:7b selected (94%, 0 misses); granite3.2-vision brittle (44%, 2 misses) despite a perfect 6/6 smoke test — a caution against trusting smoke tests; moondream is prose-only and unusable for yes/no gating. (2) Coding-correctness bench — tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts + coding-golden.ts — self-contained edit/implement/fix/parse tasks graded by writing the model's code block to a temp dir and running an assert driver via tsx (pass@1 + latency + tokens + output cleanliness). Result: qwen3-coder selected (4/4, fastest full-passer, terse); devstral-small-2 and gpt-oss:20b also 4/4; the large general model nemotron3:33b was the worst coder here (3/4, slowest, ~10x tokens) — reserve big reasoning models for planning, not code grunt work. Operational lesson baked into both harnesses: local models default to very large context windows (up to 128k) which balloon KV-cache VRAM and can crash larger vision runtimes under contention, so the benches pin a small num_ctx (sized to hold one screenshot / prompt) and unload each model between runs. SHIPPED 2026-07-07. Phase 2 SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tool-loop agentic coding bench — tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts + agentic-tasks.ts — drives each local model through a real tool-calling loop (list_files/read_file/write_file/run_tests/finish) in a sandbox, measuring pass@1, turns, self-verification, scope discipline, and spiral rate. Result: devstral-small-2 top (0.98, all pass, fewest turns, ~366 tokens), qwen3-coder and gpt-oss:20b also perfect; nemotron3:33b failed a third time (33% pass, spiraled, 6225 tokens, self-verified once) — consistent across all three benches that big reasoning models are wrong for coding/agentic grunt work. Cost bench SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts + cost-golden.ts — compares Opus-token cost of full-system vs Opus-alone on graph-grounded generation, three arms (A0 Opus+raw graph, A1 Opus+kb_compress-style compressed subgraph, A2 local drafts + Opus reviews), inferring $ from live API usage. Result (Opus 4.8, ~$0.48 spend): A1 and A2 both 79% cheaper than A0 at identical 100% quality — the graph compression is the dominant lever (6x fewer input tokens); local delegation adds little on short outputs and pays only when OUTPUT is large (Opus output tokens at $25/Mtok are the expensive ones). Extended 2026-07-07: a long-form (~700-word) generation task confirmed the delegation win — A2 (local writes, Opus reviews/approves) 77% cheaper than A0 vs A1's 66%, because the expensive OUTPUT is generated free locally; and raw context proved LOWER quality here — the full raw graph scored 60% fact-coverage vs 80% for the compressed subgraph (needle-in-haystack). Capacity note: the whole static graph is ~116k tokens — fits comfortably in Opus's 1M window, but feeding it raw costs ~50x more per query than a compressed subgraph and can ground worse; compression is a cost+quality lever, not a capacity workaround. Harness comparison (OpenCode, Qwen Code): both are built for interactive use and their headless local-model paths are immature — OpenCode ships no local-Ollama provider (only ollama-cloud; needs manual provider config), Qwen Code defaults to qwen-oauth cloud — observed opening a browser to chat.qwen.ai for login even in headless -p mode — and even wired neither completed a trivial fix headlessly in 120s via the OpenAI-compatible /v1 path (~13s cold per call), whereas the minimal custom tool-loop and Claude Code complete the same tasks in seconds. Qualitative conclusion (matching hands-on experience): Claude Code's harness has materially lower friction/overhead for local-model agent work; a clean headless pass-rate comparison would need long timeouts and per-tool auth/config work not yet done." .

