kb:import-workspace-ux
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:relates-to kb:sveltia-edit-mapping ;
    pred:feature-id "F50" ;
    pred:description "Fix the confusing import + workspace/graph-settings experience (user feedback 2026-07-09: 'how horrible the import and workspace/graph settings are right now'). PROBLEMS: (a) graph-data actions (import graphs from folder, sync) live in GLOBAL Settings, far from where graphs are managed; (b) the nav item labeled 'graph' goes to /kb (registry) while the graph VIEW is / — so 'graph settings' has no obvious home; (c) 'sync all graphs now' (WRITE: browser graphs -> folder) reads as the same thing as 'import graphs from folder' (READ: folder -> browser), and the count/'3 graphs' compounds the confusion; (d) importing a bare .ttl silently loses binary assets (icons/previews/models) — folder import restores them (partly addressed: an import-time warning now points to folder import). DIRECTION: (1) surface graph import/export ON the graph page (/kb) where graphs are managed — the user's choice — keeping detailed workspace CONFIG in Settings; (2) clearly separate and label the two DIRECTIONS (push-to-folder vs pull-from-folder) with plain wording and per-direction affordances; (3) make import asset-aware (prefer conventional kbs/{name}/ folders that carry assets; warn on loose/bare .ttl); (4) reconsider naming ('graph' nav vs graph view). Relates to F48 (Sveltia edit routing, the other workspace-branch surface), F27 publishing, and the recursive folder-discovery fix. Small deterministic wins land first; the fuller IA rework is scoped here." ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    rdfs:label "Import & Workspace UX Rework" .

kb:graph-ordering
    pred:feature-id "F39" ;
    pred:description "Order the roadmap and other reference graphs properly using the existing nav vocabulary (hnav: = urn:reckons:nav/, consumed by src/lib/rdf/hierarchy.ts): hnav:order (position, meta/hidden), skos:broader (tree parent), hnav:layer (depth), hnav:next/hnav:prev (visible sequence edges). Adds a NEW hnav:sequential \"true\"^^xsd:boolean flag on a parent/story node meaning its ordered children are a LOCKED front-to-back reading (no random access) — 'a story can sometimes only be read front to back'. First worked target: the enterprise phase chain (kb:ent-phase-1..4) and currents phases as ordered, sequential sub-trees; then a full pass tagging feature epics/themes as tree parents. hierarchy.ts + the story player need to learn hnav:sequential to enforce the locked traversal." ;
