kb:local-offload
    pred:relates-to kb:cost-awareness ;
    pred:depends-on kb:llm-providers ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:description "Offload token-heavy LLM work to local models (Ollama) with quality recovered through intelligent instruction. Schema-constrained decoding via Ollama's native /api/chat format parameter plus a compact few-shot extractor prompt for small models (src/lib/integrations/llm/ollama-extract.ts). Measured (2026-07-02, tests/bench/results): llama3.2:3b ingest F1 0.238 baseline -> 0.500 structured (combined 0.657 — the new best local score, surpassing devstral-small-2's 0.649 with a 2GB model); qwen3:4b 0.000 -> 0.263; devstral-small-2 structured ingest 0.486 (its chat leg did not run in that pass). Children: the MCP Ollama bridge and prefer-local routing (settings.preferLocal + VITE_PREFER_LOCAL: chat, diff summary, and merge analysis default to Ollama when reachable — probe cached 60s via src/lib/integrations/llm/prefer-local.ts — with explicit per-task overrides always winning)." ;
    rdfs:label "Local LLM Offload" ;
    pred:has-status "functional" .

kb:question-context-pages
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:description "An OPTIONAL short context/summary page attached to a specific pending triple or '? question' fact, to give the reviewer what they need to decide. MOTIVATION: the Review tab surfaces partial facts needing an answer (F32 — incoming.needsObject, the 'questions only' filter in routes/(app)/review/+page.svelte), but a bare subject-predicate-? is often not enough context to accept/answer/reject confidently. DESIGN (reuses F27 + F44): the page is a WebPage-like node authored in Sveltia (content/*.md <-> graph round-trip), linked to the question via kpred:context-for -> [the statement/question id or subject IRI], rendered inline in the review card as an expandable summary (excerpt in graph, long-form in the .md). Content can be human-written OR drafted by Shelly grounded in the graph (kb_generate_page / kb_entity_markdown / kb_compress) then edited. Distinct from the answer itself (knowledge.answers.jsonl) — this is decision-support context, not the decision. Kept optional and lightweight so most questions need none. More urgent than F44's change-note use because it unblocks review throughput directly. Relates to F32 partial facts, F44 change notes, and F27 publishing." ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:change-notes ;
    rdfs:label "Triple-Question Context Pages" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:partial-facts ;
    pred:feature-id "F46" ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> .

kb:change-notes
    pred:description "A first-class ChangeNote + Approval layer over the graph. MOTIVATION: pending->confirmed handles short facts, but some changes need (a) long-form human PROSE explaining the why, (b) an APPROVAL trail (who signed off, when), and (c) automatic links to the OTHER nodes whose state the change moved — none of which fit a bare triple. DESIGN (graph-first, reuses F27): a ChangeNote is a WebPage-like node authored through Sveltia CMS (the existing content/*.md <-> graph round-trip in src/lib/publish/), so the long-form body lives in markdown and the structured metadata lives as triples: kpred:notes-change-to -> [affected entity IRIs] (rendered as leap-style back-links on those nodes — the 'links to node state in a slightly different way'), kpred:state-transition -> a reified from->to on each affected node (before/after status), kpred:approval-status (proposed|approved|rejected), kpred:approved-by, kpred:approved-on. An Approval is its own small shape reused across the app so three things share ONE model: F33 release-gate sign-offs (kpred:dev-approved / stakeholder-approved), F35 steering-committee votes, and note-level approvals. The md-align check (F27) keeps note bodies honest against the graph. Distinct from pending.jsonl (short machine-proposed facts) — ChangeNotes are human-authored, long-form, and approval-bearing. PHASES: (1) ChangeNote graph shape + a Sveltia collection in static/admin/config.yml + render on affected nodes; (2) Approval shape + status transitions surfaced in the Review tab; (3) unify F33/F35 approvals onto it. Grounded in graphs-are-source-of-truth: notes and approvals travel with the graph as ordinary Turtle." ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:relates-to kb:steering-committee ;
    pred:feature-id "F44" ;
    rdfs:label "Change Notes & Approval Tracking" ;
    pred:priority "medium" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:release-pipeline .

kb:release-pipeline
    pred:has-status "functional" ;
    pred:description "Model the release pipeline in the graphs and check branches against it. Three environments with review gates (static/reckons-production.ttl): kb:env-dev (branch dev, DEVELOPER technical review), kb:env-staging (branch staging, STAKEHOLDER business review), kb:env-production (branch main, both approvals; deploys on push). Features carry promotion predicates: kpred:in-dev / kpred:in-staging / kpred:in-production (dated), plus kpred:dev-approved / kpred:stakeholder-approved sign-offs; has-status 'production' implies in-production. scripts/branch-align.ts parses these claims and compares them to real git state (branch existence, main..branch merged PRs), reporting the pipeline per environment and flagging drift: features marked in-dev but status 'production' (contradiction), 'functional' features not marked in any env (untracked), in-dev features already on main (should promote to production status), missing env branches, and merged PRs on a branch not reflected by any tracked feature (unplanned). Run: npm run branch-align. Complements the code<->Graph alignment in scripts/kb-align.ts (F26) by adding the environment/branch dimension. Development lifecycle — each gate reviews against a graph: (1) BUSINESS DEFINITION of the feature in the roadmap graph (business-goal level, stakeholder-owned); (2) developer + Opus orchestrate the technical spec in the CODEBASE graph; (3) local agents do the task work; (4) PR to dev; (5) DEVELOPER gate — collaborative review of the dev deploy (dev.reckons-ai.pages.dev) with visual-testing agents (VLM), confirming the implementation against the codebase graph -> kpred:dev-approved; (6) merge to staging; (7) STAKEHOLDER gate — business review on staging.reckons-ai.pages.dev of the built feature against the ORIGINAL roadmap goal (does the result meet the intent) -> kpred:stakeholder-approved; (8) agent-assisted DOCUMENTATION generation, reviewed by the stakeholder; (9) merge to main (production, reckons.ai). Env nodes carry kpred:deploy-url and kpred:reviews-graph (dev->codebase technical spec, staging->roadmap business intent); production requires-documentation." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:git-analysis ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:feature-id "F33" ;
    pred:in-dev "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
    rdfs:label "Release Pipeline & Branch Alignment" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:ci-cd-kb-watch .

